{"message":"Access to this API is not available for your account"}

This implementation is quite problematic, especially for abstract types. Perhaps some conditional logic could be applied, such as:

```python
class SubclassWithMeta_Meta:
    def __repr__(cls):
        # return cls._meta.name
        if not hasattr(cls, '__meta__'):
            return type.__repr__(cls)
        return "<{} as {}>".format(type.__repr__(cls), cls._meta.name)
```

Without this, we get into AttributeError issues where a class doesn't necessarily have a `_meta`, and it's a bit unclear what we're actually looking at. I agree that sharing the graphql name is nice, so we oughta retain that.

I'd be happy to submit a PR with tests if @syrusakbary agrees.

https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/0b92d3dba64f438e97a955d13f2ec542705d1e5e/graphene/utils/subclass_with_meta.py#L11

- OS Platform, Distribution, and Version: Windows 10
- Python Distribution and Version: Anaconda 5.2.0, Python 3.6.5 :: Anaconda, Inc.
- Java Distribution and Version: java 10.0.2 2018-07-17
- Jep Version: 3.8.1
- Python packages used (e.g. numpy, pandas, tensorflow): numpy

Minimal code example to reproduce an issue:
```java
import jep.Jep;
import jep.JepConfig;
import jep.JepException;

public class JepOutputIssue {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws JepException {
        Jep jep = new JepConfig()
                .setRedirectOutputStreams(false)
                .setInteractive(false)
                .createJep();
        jep.eval("import numpy as np");

        //Works fine if repeated 122 times or less
        for (int i = 0; i < 123; i++) {
            jep.eval("a = np.eye(3, 3)");
            jep.eval("b = np.eye(3, 3)");
            jep.eval("np.dot(a, b)");
        }

        System.out.println("done");
    }
}
```
If the `for` loop above repeated for 122 time or less, then only "done" is printed to console, as expected. However if repeated for 123 times or more, then lots of
```
array([[1., 0., 0.],
       [0., 1., 0.],
       [0., 0., 1.]])
```
messages (result of last expression) are dumped to console, just like when output is redirected by `setRedirectOutputStreams(true)`

The exact number of iterations when it happens depends on what python code is doing. But is the same for the same code. In my working code it happens after 10. For the example above it is 122 on my machine. Unfortunately I don't have a possibility to try on different OS/machine at the moment.

My current workaround is to assign the result of last expression to dummy variable which is never read, i.e. change `np.dot(a, b)` to `r = np.dot(a, b)` in the example above.

Anyway, this behavior is really strange and since I spent some time to nail it down to small code snippet, I decided to submit this bug report. Maybe you have some clue on what's going on.

Please feel free to close this issue if it is too weird or hard to reproduce.
